<article><div>
  <h2>A css document is grouped into blocks of code called <mark>rulesets</mark>.</h2>
  <p>Here's the syntax for a ruleset.</p>
<pre class='major language-css'><code>
selector{
  property: value;
  property: value;
}
</code></pre>
<p>...and here's what that looks like with actual css.</p>
<pre class='major language-css'><code>
h1{
  font-size: 11px;
  color: #000;
}
</code></pre>

<p>In this example <code>h1</code> is the selector. 
<br/>Contained in the brackets <code>{}</code> are style properties and values.
<br/>Properties are separated from values with a colon. Each property/value pair ends with a semicolon.
<br/>This ruleset will apply a font size of 11px and a black text color to every <code>h1</code> element on the page.
</p>

</div></article>

