<article><div>
  <h2>Today we'll cover 4 types of css selectors.</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>The <a href='http://www.w3schools.com/cssref/sel_element.asp'>element selector</a></li>
    <li>The <a href='http://www.w3schools.com/cssref/sel_class.asp'>class selector</a></li>
    <li><a href='http://www.w3schools.com/cssref/sel_element_element.asp'>Nested selectors</a></li>
    <li><a href='http://www.w3schools.com/cssref/sel_element_comma.asp'>Selector lists</a></li>
  </ol>
  <a class='button' href='http://www.w3schools.com/cssref/css_selectors.asp'>Full list of available selectors</a>
</div></article>

<article><div>
  <h4>1. The Element Selector</h4>
  <p>Selects elements based on their html tag names.</p>
<pre class='language-markup'><code>
  &lt;h1&gt;...&lt;/h1&gt;
  &lt;div&gt;...&lt;/div&gt;
</code></pre>

<pre class='language-css'><code>
  /* selects all h1 elements */
  h1{
    ...
  }

  /* selects all div elements */
  div{
    ...
  }
</code></pre>

</div></article>

<article><div>
  <h4>2. The Class Selector</h4>
  <p>Matches elements based on their <em>class(es)</em>. <strong>Unlike html tags, there are no pre-defined classes in css.</strong></p>
  <p>The class selector syntax is a period before the class name.</p>
  <h6>Example of the class selector syntax</h6>
<pre class='major language-css'><code>
.example{
  color: red;
}
</code></pre>

<pre class='language-markup'><code>
&lt;div class='major'&gt;...&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class='minor'&gt;...&lt;/div&gt;
</code></pre>
<pre class='language-css'><code>
/* selects all elements with a 'major' class */
.major{
  background-color: #c30;
}

/* selects all elements with a 'minor' class */
.minor{
  background-color: #f90;
}
</code></pre>

</div></article>

<article><div>
  <h4>3. Nested Selectors</h4>
  <p>The convention for selecting elements that are nested inside other elements.</p>
  <p>The syntax for specifying nested selectors is to separate each element with a space.</p>
  <p>Any number of ancestors can be specified.</p>
  <p><strong>Note</strong> that the rules are applied to the last element in the list and not to the chain ancestors.</p>
<pre class='major language-css'><code>
ancestor ancestor element{
  color: red;
}
</code></pre>

 <pre class='language-markup'><code>
  &lt;footer&gt;
    &lt;section class='major'&gt;
      &lt;div&gt;...&lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;/section&gt;
  &lt;/footer&gt;
</code></pre>

<pre class='language-css'><code>
  /* selects all divs nested inside a footer tag */
  footer div{
    ...
  }

  /* selects all divs nested inside a footer tag */
  footer div{
    ...
  }

  /* selects all divs nested inside section tags nested inside a footer tag */
  footer section div{
    ...
  }

  /* nesting is not limited to element selectors. Class selectors can be intermingled.*/
  footer .major div{
    ...
  }
</code></pre> 
</div></article>

<article><div>
  <h4>4. Selector Lists</h4>
  <p>The convention for applying rules to multiple selectors.</p>
  <p>The syntax for listing selectors is to separate each element with a comma.</p>
  <p>In the example below, the css styles would be applied to every <code>h1</code>, <code>h2</code> and <code>p</code> as well as any tag with a <code>major</code> class.</p>
<pre class='major language-css'><code>
h1, h2, .major, p{
  color: red;
}
</code></pre>

</div></article>

